Yeah, let me give a very concrete example of this. So as

00:23:15.439 --> 00:23:18.880
I imagine most people on this call, no, it is generally best

00:23:18.880 --> 00:23:23.040
if you have code in a shared repository that people commit

00:23:23.040 --> 00:23:25.359
and push and pull. It is generally worse if you have a

00:23:25.359 --> 00:23:28.079
data science team where everyone has everything on their own

00:23:28.079 --> 00:23:31.119
laptop with no structure and different formats, like maybe

00:23:31.119 --> 00:23:33.439
they run this report once a week, but if they threw away the

00:23:33.439 --> 00:23:38.319
laptop, you have to rebuild the whole report. So I had one at

00:23:38.319 --> 00:23:41.040
one of my consulting things I'd gone just from just from being

00:23:41.040 --> 00:23:43.520
a team where everyone uses Git and we all have a clear system

00:23:43.520 --> 00:23:46.719
with folders and blah, blah, blah, to a team of 30 data

00:23:46.719 --> 00:23:50.079
scientists, 90% of them didn't use Git. Some of them, like I

00:23:50.079 --> 00:23:54.400
said, use SPSS, blah, blah, blah. And that is bad. That is

00:23:54.400 --> 00:23:57.920
bad for a lot of reasons. If someone were to leave, that

00:23:57.920 --> 00:24:00.479
company would be really bad. We can't even keep track of what

00:24:00.479 --> 00:24:02.959
code actually is running in prod because everyone has their

00:24:02.959 --> 00:24:07.439
own stuff. Now, when I come in to be like, I objectively know

00:24:07.439 --> 00:24:10.000
that the team I've just been working on before with Git and

00:24:10.000 --> 00:24:13.599
folders and whatever, CICD, that is objectively better. But

00:24:13.599 --> 00:24:17.599
to try and do the work of getting everyone to switch to

00:24:17.599 --> 00:24:20.560
using Git and a shared language, that is a massive amount of

00:24:20.560 --> 00:24:23.119
work. I could not do that. I don't even think, and I've

00:24:23.119 --> 00:24:25.280
thought about this a lot, I don't even think the person

