00:25:04.079 --> 00:25:06.719
So there's actually, there's an anonymous question that just

00:25:06.719 --> 00:25:10.719
came in on how do you structure internal documentation or

00:25:10.719 --> 00:25:14.079
communication channels so people can be empowered by the

00:25:14.079 --> 00:25:15.439
internal data science team?

00:25:17.599 --> 00:25:21.199
So I have maybe two hot takes that I think are maybe not

00:25:21.199 --> 00:25:25.760
generally, like, standard, what people believe. One is I think

00:25:25.760 --> 00:25:28.959
that a lot of times data science teams write too much

00:25:28.959 --> 00:25:32.079
documentation. And two, I don't think they put it in the right

00:25:32.079 --> 00:25:34.560
place or they don't think enough about what the right place for

00:25:34.560 --> 00:25:38.000
it is, which is to say, let's say I am a data science team and

00:25:38.000 --> 00:25:42.000
we have some stakeholders work with us. One thing you might say

00:25:42.000 --> 00:25:44.239
is like, well, the stakeholders, he's asking us questions. So

00:25:44.239 --> 00:25:45.839
what I'm going to do is I'm going to write like a doc on our

00:25:45.839 --> 00:25:48.640
wiki page, and it's going to be a huge doc with every question

00:25:48.640 --> 00:25:51.359
answered in it. And a data science team will spend weeks

00:25:51.359 --> 00:25:54.079
building this giant repository of all this information. And

00:25:54.079 --> 00:25:56.640
then what do you know? The first thing is no one looks at it

00:25:56.640 --> 00:25:58.640
because it has too much information. Even if they did

00:25:58.640 --> 00:26:01.040
look at it, everyone has new weird questions that show up. So

00:26:01.040 --> 00:26:04.160
they, those docs wouldn't really answer it. The docs are

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:07.040
written to avoid having to take meetings and stuff with these

00:26:07.040 --> 00:26:09.680
people. But in fact, you still have to take just as much

00:26:09.680 --> 00:26:11.520
meetings. Now you've just spent weeks of time building

00:26:11.520 --> 00:26:14.000
something that you then also have to maintain. So I think

00:26:14.000 --> 00:26:16.719
there's a natural data science feeling of like, well, if I

00:26:16.719 --> 00:26:18.560
just write everything down, people will stop talking to me

00:26:18.560 --> 00:26:21.839
anymore. I don't think that is generally true. I think the

00:26:21.839 --> 00:26:26.479
best kind of documentation data scientists can do is one for

00:26:26.479 --> 00:26:29.760
themselves. I think within your code, having read me is having

00:26:29.760 --> 00:26:31.920
your functions documented, having good testing, good

00:26:31.920 --> 00:26:34.000
variable names. Like that's what I do really think helps

00:26:34.000 --> 00:26:37.280
quite immensely. And making sure all this code lives in a

00:26:37.280 --> 00:26:40.079
shared place where it's not like we have a GitHub repo for

00:26:40.079 --> 00:26:42.239
one thing and a GitLab repo for another, blah, blah, blah.

00:26:42.239 --> 00:26:45.359
Like just having things organized is just as valuable as

00:26:45.359 --> 00:26:48.880
documented. And then the other thing I think is that, yeah,

00:26:48.880 --> 00:26:51.520
you really can't document your way out of talking to

00:26:51.520 --> 00:26:54.160
stakeholders. And the best thing you can do is just getting

00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:57.040
it. So stakeholders know that what is the most effective way

00:26:57.040 --> 00:26:59.680
to communicate with you? Is that if they have a request, you

00:26:59.680 --> 00:27:02.800
drop it in the JIRA board? Is it, hey, there's this, this is

00:27:02.800 --> 00:27:05.040
the project manager. They always take the meetings. Like

00:27:05.040 --> 00:27:08.800
just having that clear system. So you can't minimize the work,

00:27:08.800 --> 00:27:11.760
but by having it in a flow, you can at least like manage it as

00:27:11.760 --> 00:27:14.719
opposed to fire drills requests coming everywhere. I think that

00:27:14.719 --> 00:27:18.239
stuff is far, far more valuable than like, yeah, let's write

00:27:18.239 --> 00:27:18.880
lots of docs.

00:27:20.800 --> 00:27:23.119
What kind of system do you use for requests?

00:27:25.280 --> 00:27:29.119
So I do think that you have a person on your team who's the

00:27:29.119 --> 00:27:31.439
project manager person, and maybe that's actually a project

00:27:31.439 --> 00:27:33.680
manager. Maybe that's the principal data scientist,

00:27:33.680 --> 00:27:36.719
whatever, but someone whose job it is to triage requests. You

00:27:36.719 --> 00:27:39.280
then have, when anyone has a request they want to make of

00:27:39.280 --> 00:27:43.680
you, they either talk to that person or drop it in the JIRA

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:46.800
board or whatever board. And then that person looks at it,

00:27:46.800 --> 00:27:49.040
tries to understand it, goes back to them, has a meeting

00:27:49.040 --> 00:27:52.000
about it to really clean it up. And then from there, the data

00:27:52.000 --> 00:27:54.160
science team tackles it. I think some sort of intake method

00:27:54.160 --> 00:27:57.359
like that works best. I think creating a standard form that

00:27:57.359 --> 00:27:59.520
they fill out, that kind of stuff doesn't really work

00:27:59.520 --> 00:28:01.680
because every question will never fit into a form because

00:28:01.680 --> 00:28:05.920
always have its weird edge cases. And I also think, yeah,

00:28:05.920 --> 00:28:08.400
I think just having a person who everyone knows the point of

00:28:08.400 --> 00:28:11.280
contact on this just makes it a lot easier. And like, I don't

00:28:11.280 --> 00:28:13.359
know, I find that job really fun. I love talking to people

00:28:13.359 --> 00:28:15.439
about what their problems are. Like, so it's not necessarily

00:28:15.439 --> 00:28:18.000
like a bad job, but it is something where you should, you

00:28:18.000 --> 00:28:20.239
should have one person who's really the point of contact on

00:28:20.239 --> 00:28:22.560
it. So it's not like, well, some requests go to me and some

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:25.119
requests go to blah, blah, blah. And some, oh, they had to

00:28:25.119 --> 00:28:26.959
have a lunch with this person back when people had lunch

00:28:26.959 --> 00:28:29.760
together. Now they have an extra request. Like having one

00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:31.040
clear point of contact really helps.

00:28:33.359 --> 00:28:37.119
Thank you. Ian, I see you asked the question in the chat

00:28:37.119 --> 00:28:41.040
around building a team up from scratch. Do you want to jump in

00:28:41.040 --> 00:28:42.800
and add any more context to that one?

00:28:43.520 --> 00:28:47.439
Sure. I, hi Jacqueline. I just wanted to know, you mentioned

00:28:47.439 --> 00:28:51.760
going in, starting all of these teams from scratch. Was there a

00:28:51.839 --> 00:28:56.719
common denominator, this common thing that you would

00:28:56.719 --> 00:29:00.560
experience in companies where there's maybe not a data

00:29:00.560 --> 00:29:05.520
centric culture or there's not a big understanding of what data

00:29:05.520 --> 00:29:09.839
science is? Was there a common thing that, you know, hurdle or

00:29:09.839 --> 00:29:13.680
something you had to overcome to kind of get buy-in or, you

00:29:13.680 --> 00:29:16.000
know, just to even start the team off?

00:29:17.599 --> 00:29:20.160
Yeah. So a couple of things. I mean, usually if they are

00:29:20.160 --> 00:29:23.520
hiring you, there's got to be like some big buy-in at the

00:29:23.520 --> 00:29:25.680
company in the sense of like, you wouldn't have been hired if

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:27.839
at least someone somewhere didn't think data science would

00:29:27.839 --> 00:29:31.920
be useful. So I have, cause I guess I would, which is to say,

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:34.560
I used to worry that like, am I going to get buy-in for this?

00:29:34.560 --> 00:29:37.199
That's kind of gone away. Usually it's like, there is

00:29:37.199 --> 00:29:40.079
buy-in, but there's a total lack of idea of how to actually

00:29:40.079 --> 00:29:43.280
make it work, which is to say, and I've had this happen a few

00:29:43.280 --> 00:29:45.680
times where you come to a company, you start a team, but

00:29:45.680 --> 00:29:47.920
the question is like, is there actually data we can use? Is

00:29:47.920 --> 00:29:50.719
this data actually useful? Right? Like, so if they hire you

00:29:50.719 --> 00:29:52.640
with the expectation of like, you're going to build machine

00:29:52.640 --> 00:29:55.920
learning models on the revenue data to blah, blah, blah. And

00:29:55.920 --> 00:29:58.319
then it turns out like two months in that, like, there's

00:29:58.319 --> 00:30:00.640
not enough data here that you'd ever be able to build models on

00:30:00.640 --> 00:30:03.680
it or stuff like that. That stuff keeps me up at night, but

00:30:03.680 --> 00:30:07.680
I don't think there's any real way to solve it besides before

00:30:07.680 --> 00:30:10.640
getting hired, really try and like probe on if this seems like

00:30:10.640 --> 00:30:13.920
a good chance for data science and really just being flexible

00:30:13.920 --> 00:30:16.959
with once you do start, like it may turn out that the actual

00:30:16.959 --> 00:30:18.880
data science work you're doing isn't what you originally

00:30:18.880 --> 00:30:20.959
expected. And it's just like, that's kind of the learning

00:30:20.959 --> 00:30:26.479
experience of being the first one. I will also say to the

00:30:26.479 --> 00:30:29.280
previous or earlier point, when you are the first data

00:30:29.280 --> 00:30:32.479
scientist you do, you are the first data scientist, everything

00:30:32.479 --> 00:30:35.599
you do sets a precedent. If you pick R or you pick Python, now

00:30:35.599 --> 00:30:38.479
everyone's going to use R or Python. If you use the Git repo

00:30:38.479 --> 00:30:41.920
or blah, blah, blah. Like, so it really, more than any other

00:30:41.920 --> 00:30:46.800
time, you being careful about what you're doing is going to

00:30:46.800 --> 00:30:52.079
pay off in the future. And also you have to, at the same time,

00:30:52.079 --> 00:30:54.319
and here's the twist, you can't just be like, I'm going to

00:30:54.319 --> 00:30:57.680
build a beautiful cathedral of Git repos, this CI, CD, blah,

00:30:57.680 --> 00:30:59.599
blah, blah, because you'll spend the next six months of

00:30:59.599 --> 00:31:02.400
your job setting up all this tooling, no one else to use it

00:31:02.400 --> 00:31:04.640
yet. And after six months of not actually doing work and just

00:31:04.640 --> 00:31:07.359
building tooling, you will be let go. And so it was all for

00:31:07.359 --> 00:31:10.000
not. So it's like, it is like a strategic game of like, where

00:31:10.000 --> 00:31:12.319
do you actually invest, given you can only do so much

00:31:12.319 --> 00:31:16.319
investing while concurrently trying to produce revenue. I

00:31:16.319 --> 00:31:18.880
think being the first data scientist is extremely fun, but

00:31:18.880 --> 00:31:20.959
that is quite a stressful thing. And like, I don't know,

00:31:20.959 --> 00:31:24.640
that's maybe not for everyone. Awesome. Thanks.

00:31:25.599 --> 00:31:29.119
It sounds like maybe that has happened before where you get

00:31:29.119 --> 00:31:31.520
there and you don't have the data that you actually need to

00:31:31.520 --> 00:31:35.920
do what they want you to do. Like how, how did you actually

00:31:35.920 --> 00:31:36.479
handle that?

00:31:37.680 --> 00:31:42.319
Well, you have to have some real frank conversations with

00:31:42.319 --> 00:31:46.000
your leadership about, Hey, you hired me to do things X, Y, and

00:31:46.000 --> 00:31:48.959
Z, but think X, Y, and Z is impossible. Let's talk about

00:31:48.959 --> 00:31:51.760
what is possible and how I can do it. And if you have a strong

00:31:51.760 --> 00:31:54.239
set of leaders, they'll be like, you are a data science expert.

00:31:54.239 --> 00:31:57.439
I trust you on that. Let's have that conversation and pivot.

00:31:57.439 --> 00:31:59.439
And if they are weak leaders, they will say, well, you just

00:31:59.439 --> 00:32:02.239
don't know enough about data science. We're going to keep

00:32:02.239 --> 00:32:04.719
doing the same thing because we know more than you. And then

00:32:04.719 --> 00:32:07.280
that is like a, I don't know, not great situation. Those are

00:32:07.280 --> 00:32:09.760
the sorts of situations where like me being here, isn't

00:32:09.760 --> 00:32:11.599
really right for me or you. So.

00:32:12.319 --> 00:32:16.719
Yeah, definitely. Julia, I see you just put a question into the

00:32:16.719 --> 00:32:21.520
chat as well on tips for denying requests. Would you want to jump

00:32:21.520 --> 00:32:23.760
in and provide any other context for that one?

00:32:24.640 --> 00:32:31.119
Sure, absolutely. So I work at a hospital where we have a fairly

00:32:31.119 --> 00:32:33.760
new data science team. And the problem with hospitals is that

00:32:33.760 --> 00:32:37.760
they tend to be very hierarchical in that everybody's

00:32:38.719 --> 00:32:41.760
first idea is always would go as high up in the hierarchy as

00:32:41.760 --> 00:32:47.439
possible to ask what we should solve. Whereas I maybe have the

00:32:47.439 --> 00:32:50.000
understanding that the good ideas actually come from the

00:32:50.000 --> 00:32:52.560
people who work with the patients and do all of the stuff

00:32:52.560 --> 00:32:56.400
where whose work we're supposed to be helping. And I haven't

00:32:56.400 --> 00:33:03.199
figured out a good way to triage where people I work with are not

00:33:03.199 --> 00:33:06.880
necessarily comfortable saying to the high ups that this is

00:33:06.880 --> 00:33:13.680
this might not be the best use of our resources. And I also am

00:33:13.680 --> 00:33:16.640
not senior enough to maybe be able to do that myself. So if

00:33:16.640 --> 00:33:20.800
you have any ideas on how to, as you say, like, try to bring the

00:33:20.800 --> 00:33:23.680
reality into the conversation, that would be really cool.

00:33:25.040 --> 00:33:27.599
So I will first say you said, well, I'm not necessarily

00:33:27.599 --> 00:33:30.800
senior enough. I think that is a student observation, which is I

00:33:30.800 --> 00:33:33.199
think a lot of times people get on these calls and do the way

00:33:33.199 --> 00:33:35.199
like you can be the lowest person in a company. And if you

00:33:35.199 --> 00:33:37.199
pitch your idea, just right, people are gonna love it. And

00:33:37.199 --> 00:33:41.439
like, that's not really like, like, positions are real. And

00:33:41.439 --> 00:33:44.319
sometimes being more senior gets stuff. So like, I think it is

00:33:45.040 --> 00:33:48.719
good that you are aware that that stuff exists, and you're

00:33:48.719 --> 00:33:53.199
navigating around that. That said, the most luck I have had

00:33:53.199 --> 00:33:56.400
in these things, in these sorts of situations is just trying to

00:33:56.400 --> 00:33:59.199
like pivot the pitch from not like, hey, more senior person,

00:33:59.199 --> 00:34:01.920
you're wrong. And here's why. Although that's maybe how I feel

00:34:01.920 --> 00:34:05.359
but much more like, hey, how can I show you, senior person,

00:34:06.079 --> 00:34:09.199
the things I am seeing that are making me think that the more

00:34:09.199 --> 00:34:11.199
junior way of doing things are, right? So like the senior

00:34:11.199 --> 00:34:13.199
person, like we need to build a whole new data platform or

00:34:13.199 --> 00:34:16.159
whatever. And you're like, no, we really just need to like, go

00:34:16.159 --> 00:34:18.399
survey some hospital beds, right? Like the more you can be

00:34:18.399 --> 00:34:21.679
like, well, let me explain why. Let me show you some data. Like

00:34:21.679 --> 00:34:24.639
the more you can kind of, it's not like, hey, I need to change

00:34:24.639 --> 00:34:27.040
your mind. It's like, I'm going to bring you into this new, even

00:34:27.040 --> 00:34:31.360
better idea. Like that's kind of thinking helps, which is to

00:34:31.360 --> 00:34:34.080
say, most of what you're kind of asking about, and I think has

00:34:34.080 --> 00:34:38.479
repeatedly come up on this call is like, organizational dynamics

00:34:38.479 --> 00:34:41.600
and like the things that have helped me the most of my career

00:34:41.600 --> 00:34:44.560
get good at these are books on like negotiation and like

00:34:44.560 --> 00:34:47.760
getting to yes and difficult conversations, just like

00:34:47.760 --> 00:34:50.879
thinking, answering the question of how do I convince another

00:34:50.879 --> 00:34:54.399
person to do the thing that I think we should do? Like that's

00:34:54.399 --> 00:34:57.280
that is totally unrelated to data science and very much like

00:34:57.280 --> 00:35:02.000
business philosophy, like argument, meta conversation, you

00:35:02.000 --> 00:35:05.199
know, like, and I think just really thinking about it that

00:35:05.199 --> 00:35:08.399
way and trying to look at those resources help. But like, it's

00:35:08.399 --> 00:35:11.919
very tricky. And it's, um, I would love I would love more

00:35:11.919 --> 00:35:13.679
than anything. I would answer be like, Oh, well, if you just

00:35:13.679 --> 00:35:16.479
said these three words, then they have to do here's the code

00:35:16.479 --> 00:35:19.760
words. But at least I have not yet found anything of the sort.

00:35:20.879 --> 00:35:24.159
That was a that was a really good tip on the looking into the

00:35:24.159 --> 00:35:26.159
negotiation literature and stuff like that. Thank you so

00:35:26.159 --> 00:35:27.360
much. You're welcome.

00:35:29.120 --> 00:35:31.760
Yeah, thank you. I was just saying in our little side note

00:35:31.760 --> 00:35:37.280
clip that that portion that was really helpful to Trevor, I see

00:35:37.280 --> 00:35:41.199
you just asked the question to around when you're the first

00:35:41.199 --> 00:35:43.760
data scientist. Do you want to jump in and ask that one?

00:35:44.959 --> 00:35:48.479
Hello, everyone. Very interesting conversation with

00:35:48.479 --> 00:35:54.479
Jacqueline, right? So you spoke about being the first data

00:35:54.479 --> 00:35:59.760
scientist in a company or a startup. It's the point that

00:35:59.760 --> 00:36:04.320
you made about also, do you have the data that you need to do

00:36:04.320 --> 00:36:07.919
data science? So I'm asking when you typically enter a

00:36:07.919 --> 00:36:12.239
company, do they have the data already? And do they have it in

00:36:12.239 --> 00:36:16.879
a way that it is useful? Or do you also have to think about

00:36:16.879 --> 00:36:19.679
the structures that you need to put in place to get this data

00:36:20.239 --> 00:36:23.679
to a stage where you can use it to build models? I don't know

00:36:24.000 --> 00:36:26.159
what your experience has been like around that.

00:36:28.080 --> 00:36:34.639
Yeah, so I think you're correct. And I think, yeah, you're the

00:36:34.639 --> 00:36:37.199
first person that the data might not be in the right format for

00:36:37.199 --> 00:36:39.520
you. And you need to figure out how to make it the right format,

00:36:39.520 --> 00:36:41.840
you might have to build your own SQL database, you might have to

00:36:42.479 --> 00:36:44.800
set up a cloud thing, like you have to do a lot more of that

00:36:44.800 --> 00:36:47.760
work than if you're an established company. Sometimes

00:36:47.760 --> 00:36:50.719
companies do have data engineering teams where they

00:36:50.719 --> 00:36:52.959
have data scientists, you know, if they have been collecting

00:36:52.959 --> 00:36:57.040
data, I know it's valuable. So like, the like, it doesn't

00:36:57.040 --> 00:36:59.360
always end up being the case, but it is quite common. And I

00:36:59.360 --> 00:37:01.360
think that's part of the tricky part of being a first data

00:37:01.360 --> 00:37:04.959
scientist. I will also say that not only do you have to be a

00:37:04.959 --> 00:37:08.959
data engineer, but I think you also have to be a data analyst,

00:37:08.959 --> 00:37:12.399
which is a lot of your job as a first data scientist might just

00:37:12.399 --> 00:37:16.959
be taking data from a CSV, summarizing it, making it into

00:37:16.959 --> 00:37:19.919
one chart in a PDF file, and then emailing it to executive,

00:37:19.919 --> 00:37:22.719
which I would argue is, it's not like data science work, it's

00:37:22.719 --> 00:37:26.479
more like analytics. But like, that's part of your job, too.

00:37:26.479 --> 00:37:28.399
And you're not going to get to always just build super cool

00:37:28.399 --> 00:37:32.320
models when you're the first person. And I think that comes

00:37:32.320 --> 00:37:34.399
with like the struggle of being the first is like, you never

00:37:34.399 --> 00:37:36.159
know exactly what your job is going to be like, and you just

00:37:36.159 --> 00:37:39.040
have to be ready to roll with whatever punch that will help

00:37:39.040 --> 00:37:42.639
grow your team and your company. Also, you I don't know if you

00:37:42.639 --> 00:37:44.560
guys have seen this, but I'm a very fidgety person. So I'm

00:37:44.560 --> 00:37:47.120
picking up like the thermostats in my speaker and everything.

00:37:47.120 --> 00:37:50.320
Yeah, so yeah, so could I ask a follow up question there?

00:37:50.320 --> 00:37:53.919
Because if first data scientists, right, so the

00:37:53.919 --> 00:37:57.360
assumption there is that the company that you're being hired

00:37:57.360 --> 00:38:01.840
in, that they know what they want, right? So when they ask

00:38:01.840 --> 00:38:05.760
for a data scientist, I mean, do you do you see them asking

00:38:05.760 --> 00:38:10.879
for someone with a background in data engineering, or they

00:38:10.879 --> 00:38:12.239
don't know what they're asking for?

00:38:12.800 --> 00:38:15.600
I think I've seen almost every time I've started, been on the

00:38:15.600 --> 00:38:18.879
start of a data science team, I think I would say 75% of the

00:38:18.879 --> 00:38:21.120
time, they did not actually know what they wanted, they

00:38:21.120 --> 00:38:24.320
knew they had data. And they knew that if you take data, it

00:38:24.320 --> 00:38:27.280
somehow turns you into money or turns it to money. Like, you

00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:29.760
know, they understood that from like, they read the Harvard

00:38:29.760 --> 00:38:31.760
Business Review articles, but they don't really know much

00:38:31.760 --> 00:38:33.919
more about that. And they know a data science person is the

00:38:33.919 --> 00:38:36.399
kind of person who does that. And so you as the first hire may

00:38:36.399 --> 00:38:38.159
have to come in and be like, actually, you don't even need

00:38:38.159 --> 00:38:40.639
me yet, you need a data engineer, or actually, what you

00:38:40.639 --> 00:38:43.199
really need is not data science, but analytics, right? Like

00:38:43.199 --> 00:38:46.479
there's so many angles that could go. And like, that's just

00:38:46.560 --> 00:38:49.120
how it is. And like, even companies that really seem like

00:38:49.120 --> 00:38:51.199
they should know what they want from data scientists, sometimes

00:38:51.199 --> 00:38:54.000
they just, unless you already have data science established,

00:38:54.000 --> 00:38:56.080
you just you don't really know what it's going to be like.

00:38:59.760 --> 00:39:03.760
Thank you. And shifting gears a little bit to hiring

00:39:03.760 --> 00:39:07.120
conversation. I see Jeff, you just asked the question about

00:39:07.120 --> 00:39:09.439
hiring new talent. Would you want to ask that live?

00:39:09.840 --> 00:39:13.439
And I can read it as well. It says, as a data science leader,

00:39:13.439 --> 00:39:17.199
what are the pros and cons of hiring new talent or trying to

00:39:17.199 --> 00:39:18.800
upskill existing talent?

00:39:21.919 --> 00:39:28.879
So I will say, I don't, I don't super, I don't super feel like

00:39:28.879 --> 00:39:36.080
it's, um, it's like a binary, I guess, I always feel like I, I

00:39:36.560 --> 00:39:40.719
binary, I guess, I always feel like I, as a leader, I always

00:39:40.719 --> 00:39:44.719
want to be upskilling my employees, which is to say, at

00:39:44.719 --> 00:39:48.080
every turn, I should be trying every day, regardless of

00:39:48.080 --> 00:39:50.320
hiring other people or anything like that, I should always be

00:39:50.320 --> 00:39:53.040
trying to make sure my employees are working on things that are

00:39:53.040 --> 00:39:55.280
challenging them and helping them grow. And they learn new

00:39:55.280 --> 00:39:58.320
skills, both because that gets me more things that they can

00:39:58.320 --> 00:40:00.320
work on at the company. And it's good for them because they get

00:40:00.320 --> 00:40:03.199
new skills and have presumably more fun doing it. So like, I

00:40:03.280 --> 00:40:05.840
just, I think that the upskilling is just like a

00:40:05.840 --> 00:40:09.040
perpetual push forward of people. And like, that's, like

00:40:09.040 --> 00:40:12.320
never changes. When it comes to like the pros and cons of

00:40:12.320 --> 00:40:15.360
hiring new talent of like, when is it valuable to your team, I

00:40:15.360 --> 00:40:19.439
really struggle with this, because I do think that when you

00:40:19.439 --> 00:40:21.840
hire more people than that, that actually is a really big

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:25.520
burden on your team, both like, you have to give them work to

00:40:25.520 --> 00:40:28.719
do and make sure they are content and communicate with

