Awesome. And going back to the question right before this,

00:41:38.239 --> 00:41:41.040
someone just asked if we could clarify maybe what is the

00:41:41.040 --> 00:41:44.560
difference between a data scientist and a data analyst?

00:41:45.760 --> 00:41:49.919
Oh, okay. Great question. I would say a data analyst job is

00:41:49.919 --> 00:41:53.199
to take raw data and get it into a consumable format for an

00:41:53.199 --> 00:41:56.159
executive, right? So if you have a SQL table, it's an

00:41:56.159 --> 00:41:59.360
analyst job to turn it into an Excel file that has just the

00:41:59.360 --> 00:42:03.280
summary monthly numbers and put that in a dashboard and these

00:42:03.280 --> 00:42:06.399
sorts of things. This is a challenging job because like,

00:42:06.399 --> 00:42:09.520
well, what are you doing with sales data? What about returned

00:42:09.520 --> 00:42:11.840
objects? And what about this? And like, well, if we do that,

00:42:11.840 --> 00:42:14.479
then that actually changes last month's numbers. And that would

00:42:14.479 --> 00:42:17.439
be weird. Can we do that? Like, there's like a lot of work and

00:42:17.439 --> 00:42:20.159
thought that has to be into getting executives that data.

00:42:20.959 --> 00:42:25.120
A data scientist, in my opinion, is a person who is more

00:42:25.120 --> 00:42:30.320
focused on, they get a data set in an abstract question of like,

00:42:30.320 --> 00:42:33.600
why are my customers churning? What is the best offer to give

00:42:33.600 --> 00:42:36.959
my customers? Things like that. And a data science job is to

00:42:36.959 --> 00:42:40.080
like build models, do regressions, forecast, whatever,

00:42:40.080 --> 00:42:42.719
to try and answer those things. So a data scientist is more

00:42:42.719 --> 00:42:45.840
about using models to answer questions and like do inference,

00:42:45.840 --> 00:42:48.639
whereas a data analyst doesn't really build models. They just

00:42:48.639 --> 00:42:52.639
take data and group, aggregate, summarize, and visualize in

00:42:52.639 --> 00:42:54.800
thoughtful ways that people within the company can use it.

00:42:55.679 --> 00:42:58.320
And I think companies have like a thousand times more data

00:42:58.320 --> 00:43:00.639
analysts work than data scientists work. And I think

00:43:00.639 --> 00:43:02.239
there are a lot of data scientists there who like, I

00:43:02.239 --> 00:43:05.199
would never do data analysts work. And I know because I used

00:43:05.199 --> 00:43:07.600
to be one and I was very snobby about this early in my career.

00:43:07.600 --> 00:43:10.000
And now I do a lot of it and it's fine. But like, there's

00:43:10.000 --> 00:43:12.560
like a mental hurdle you have to get over of like, things

00:43:12.560 --> 00:43:15.760
aren't less interesting or numerically challenging just

00:43:15.760 --> 00:43:17.280
because they don't have a regression in them.

00:43:17.919 --> 00:43:23.840
So on the topic of roles, I see, Will, you just asked a

