you mentioned kind of a project manager earlier, data

00:43:33.280 --> 00:43:36.479
engineer, data scientist. What do you recommend as far as

00:43:36.479 --> 00:43:38.639
the types of roles in a data science team?

00:43:39.439 --> 00:43:42.560
It's super depends on what your team is doing. If your

00:43:42.560 --> 00:43:46.719
team is like primarily like making reports, doing analysis,

00:43:46.719 --> 00:43:49.280
like doing an analytical, like trying to answer these

00:43:49.280 --> 00:43:52.800
questions with data. That is different than you're building

00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:54.800
actual models that are going into production, that sort of

00:43:54.800 --> 00:43:57.199
thing. I think, I mean, obviously you need data

00:43:57.199 --> 00:43:59.840
scientists. I think after you have like two or three data

00:43:59.840 --> 00:44:02.639
scientists, you probably want to have like a principal person

00:44:02.639 --> 00:44:06.560
or like this, a person who is like job it is to like coach

00:44:06.560 --> 00:44:09.040
and help out on the other data scientists. So I think you

00:44:09.040 --> 00:44:13.280
need a lot of that. I also do think having someone whose job

00:44:13.280 --> 00:44:16.000
it is to do project management, which is could very well be

00:44:16.000 --> 00:44:20.959
that principal. That's valuable too. I think having a manager

00:44:20.959 --> 00:44:24.239
is good if you get big enough. Again, a principal style person

00:44:24.239 --> 00:44:27.360
can also be a manager and a manager could be a project

00:44:27.360 --> 00:44:30.000
manager. So there's all kind of overlap, but like, okay, so let

00:44:30.000 --> 00:44:33.199
me, I'm going to start over. Here's what you need. You need

00:44:33.199 --> 00:44:36.479
data scientists to do the work. You need someone whose job it

00:44:36.479 --> 00:44:39.280
is to help those people technically when they're not

00:44:39.280 --> 00:44:42.239
sure about stuff, which could be convincing them to do unit

00:44:42.239 --> 00:44:45.439
tests or whatever, and checking for that. You need someone

00:44:45.439 --> 00:44:47.679
who's a manager whose job it is to figure out that the work

00:44:47.679 --> 00:44:50.959
coming in makes sense, right? Like a manager's job is to like,

00:44:50.959 --> 00:44:53.840
hey, are we asking, are we working on the right stuff? Are

00:44:53.840 --> 00:44:57.439
we asking right tests? Are our employees growing and are they

00:44:57.439 --> 00:44:59.520
getting the right comp or whatever? Like that kind of

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:02.239
stuff. And you need someone who's a project manager, which

00:45:02.239 --> 00:45:05.760
is like literally like, hey, person X from this department

00:45:05.760 --> 00:45:08.560
asks us to do this. Does that request make sense? Do we need

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:11.520
to flesh it out? How does that fit into our like list of work?

00:45:12.000 --> 00:45:15.360
That's like five roles on that team. A lot of those can be

00:45:15.360 --> 00:45:18.239
bunched into the same person, but depending on what your

00:45:18.239 --> 00:45:20.800
company is like, it may make sense to do that bunching

00:45:20.800 --> 00:45:23.840
differently. In like the most abstract case, you have three

00:45:23.840 --> 00:45:27.520
data scientists and manager, principal, project manager,

00:45:27.520 --> 00:45:30.320
person does all the other stuff. But I think it really

00:45:30.320 --> 00:45:37.919
depends. Thank you. So follow-up question from the

